188
00:18:59,185 --> 00:19:00,045
[SPEAKER_10]: I know that that,

189
00:19:00,585 --> 00:19:03,886
[SPEAKER_10]: that part of Boston Avenue that leads into Ball Square.

190
00:19:03,926 --> 00:19:19,271
[SPEAKER_10]: It's a very interesting transition kind of from a neighborhood that seems immediately like residential plus the big apartment building and then goes right into Ball Square.

191
00:19:19,411 --> 00:19:26,573
[SPEAKER_10]: So it's an interesting part of the city where you start to where it kind of like

192
00:19:26,973 --> 00:19:34,879
[SPEAKER_10]: starts to transition from the more dense residential of South Medford into some more commercial areas.

193
00:19:34,979 --> 00:19:41,864
[SPEAKER_10]: So that I do personally feel like it's worth considering.

194
00:19:42,484 --> 00:19:55,954
[SPEAKER_10]: Also, just because a lot of, with some of these presentations, I am realizing how many of those areas under Boston Avenue are non-conforming and are just a little bit, have a lot of random things

195
00:19:56,794 --> 00:19:57,895
[SPEAKER_10]: sort of thrown into them.

196
00:19:58,395 --> 00:20:07,140
[SPEAKER_10]: So that is, those are just two aspects that I feel like are topically related, even though the geographies do tend to be a little bit different.

197
00:20:07,981 --> 00:20:17,106
[SPEAKER_10]: I would like your, I would like some of your thoughts, um, on first, and this could be a PDS question as well.

198
00:20:17,126 --> 00:20:26,112
[SPEAKER_10]: Why, what sort of led to a lot of this nonconformity, like historically, and how, how is it usually dealt with in zone and

199
00:20:27,313 --> 00:20:29,196
[SPEAKER_10]: Um, and zoning changes.

200
00:20:29,216 --> 00:20:38,747
[SPEAKER_10]: Um, I know that you might not have, like, the whole history of all this stuff here, but if that is something that you could just comment on from your own expertise.

201
00:20:40,009 --> 00:20:46,477
[SPEAKER_06]: Um, I'm happy to comment on it and sort of the general aspect, uh, with not necessarily going into specifics.

202
00:20:47,187 --> 00:20:55,513
[SPEAKER_06]: Part of it is it's just it's New England in that zoning really didn't come into play until actually 100 years ago.

203
00:20:55,953 --> 00:21:02,797
[SPEAKER_06]: Happy anniversary Euclidean zoning from 1926 court case that really talked to the separation of uses.

204
00:21:02,877 --> 00:21:05,899
[SPEAKER_06]: It's not that cities haven't separated uses before.

205
00:21:06,080 --> 00:21:06,680
[SPEAKER_06]: It's just

206
00:21:07,999 --> 00:21:17,607
[SPEAKER_06]: They hadn't done so at the sort of the scale and depth that was authorized after this particular court case.

207
00:21:17,967 --> 00:21:28,516
[SPEAKER_06]: But what happened, of course, is if you think about it, a lot of our New England cities and towns, villages were already starting to be built out prior to zoning coming in.

208
00:21:29,157 --> 00:21:34,722
[SPEAKER_06]: And then in some cases, the zoning that was put in later was aspirational rather than

209
00:21:35,342 --> 00:21:47,275
[SPEAKER_06]: Matching what was on the ground and so we have that combination of uses also fairly historically we had smaller scale commercial mixed in with with neighborhood uses as well.

210
00:21:47,315 --> 00:21:53,681
[SPEAKER_06]: I can think of any number of towns where they had corner stores that have since disappeared over the years, for example, so.

211
00:21:54,482 --> 00:22:05,691
[SPEAKER_06]: In general, our development patterns frequently in the New England area frequently do not match what's in the zoning because those development patterns were already set.

212
00:22:06,352 --> 00:22:14,218
[SPEAKER_06]: We also have to look at the fact that many people were not, you know, necessarily owning automobiles.

213
00:22:14,258 --> 00:22:18,462
[SPEAKER_06]: Some of those smaller lots, for example, I see it in Medford here.

214
00:22:18,582 --> 00:22:20,443
[SPEAKER_06]: I see it in other parts of

215
00:22:21,465 --> 00:22:31,433
[SPEAKER_06]: Massachusetts, where we might have triple deckers in particular, or two families where they were walking to local neighborhoods.

216
00:22:31,534 --> 00:22:35,517
[SPEAKER_06]: Actually, it's kind of interesting that that idea of walkability has come around.

217
00:22:36,045 --> 00:22:38,926
[SPEAKER_06]: But they didn't have to do car storage on their lots.

218
00:22:39,046 --> 00:22:44,369
[SPEAKER_06]: They might have had a tram or a trolley that came down the street.

219
00:22:44,449 --> 00:22:48,511
[SPEAKER_06]: They might have had local goods and services relatively close.

220
00:22:48,551 --> 00:22:55,594
[SPEAKER_06]: They might have had only one member of the family commuting into the city to work, and that was walkable to a train station.

221
00:22:55,774 --> 00:23:02,877
[SPEAKER_06]: So some of those triple-deckers you would never be able to build now because they can't have that amount of parking on that lot.

222
00:23:03,527 --> 00:23:18,162
[SPEAKER_06]: So that's where a lot of these things come in and that's why I talk about the need to consider how much nonconforming you have if you're doing a zoning change because many people want to preserve these neighborhoods that have these close relationships between the buildings.

223
00:23:18,802 --> 00:23:25,503
[SPEAKER_06]: But if you're making it harder to invest in by having them be non-conforming, you definitely want to address that.

224
00:23:25,563 --> 00:23:27,064
[SPEAKER_06]: So that's that stage one.

225
00:23:27,444 --> 00:23:42,547
[SPEAKER_06]: And then the question becomes for some of the larger lots, for some of the commercial uses you might want over time, for areas that you do want to see develop, how do you think about what is the aspirational aspect of that where you want to allow something new to happen?

226
00:23:43,385 --> 00:23:49,531
[SPEAKER_06]: And then it's the, how do you have that transition of the new respecting the old?

227
00:23:49,571 --> 00:23:50,612
[SPEAKER_06]: And where does that happen?

228
00:23:50,632 --> 00:23:54,416
[SPEAKER_06]: So those are kind of the three things that we're thinking of as we look at this area.

229
00:23:54,776 --> 00:23:58,419
[SPEAKER_06]: But the nonconformities are really those historical development patterns.

230
00:23:58,900 --> 00:24:00,782
[SPEAKER_06]: And then who put in the zoning?

231
00:24:00,822 --> 00:24:03,564
[SPEAKER_06]: What were they thinking at the time that they put in the zoning?

232
00:24:03,584 --> 00:24:05,446
[SPEAKER_06]: Did they want something to change?

233
00:24:05,466 --> 00:24:07,448
[SPEAKER_06]: Were they looking for that ideal aspect?

234
00:24:08,397 --> 00:24:11,580
[SPEAKER_06]: Why were they not considering at the time what was on the ground?

235
00:24:11,620 --> 00:24:15,804
[SPEAKER_06]: And for that, I'd have to delve deeper into Medford's zoning history to understand.

236
00:24:15,824 --> 00:24:17,265
[SPEAKER_10]: Great.

237
00:24:18,306 --> 00:24:18,807
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

